description: Gateway Classic Cars of Philadelphia presents this great 1966 Ford Mustang C Code. Introduced in 1964 the 1966 Mustang debuted with moderate trim changes including a new grille, side ornamentation, wheel covers and gas cap. It also removed the Falcon instrument cluster; the previously optional features, including the round gauges and padded sun visors, became standard equipment. In 1966 A  C Code Mustang meant that the car came from the factory with the very desirable 289 V8. This one came in Emberglo Metallic with Emberglo Crinkle Vinyl and Parchment Crinkle Vinyl Interior. When this car left the factory, she was equipped with a two-barrel carburetor and three speed transmission. It is now upgraded to a Four Barrel carb and a four-speed trans. This car is a survivor car that has had some restoration work done to it. The interior has been updated with newer seat covers in the original color and design. An aftermarket console has been added and looks like it was always there. In the glove box, you will find a modern stereo with a CD player as well. The car has been repainted, in the original color. The original wheel covers are still on the car and add to that stock factory look that this car still has. This is a driver quality car that has had some performance modifications while maintaining its factory appearance. This Mustang has plenty to offer and is ready to be enjoyed by its new owner. To view this 1966 Ford Mustang in greater detail, including HD pictures and an HD video, visit www.GatewayClassicCars.com or our Philadelphia showroom located in West Deptford, NJ. For more information, please call 856-599-4100 or email Philadelphia@GatewayClassicCars.com

description: This is a true dream car.  A first-year 1965 Ford Mustang convertible that's such a red-blooded American that it's fully red inside and out.  And because we know you want to drive it, the four-on-the-floor keeps you in complete control of the V8.  Who knew your dream could be this obtainable?

The red is a factory-correct color, and this great pony shows well in the sun.  Iconic cruisers like this always get the attention, and that's why a bright red Mustang is always in demand.  Plus, the sheetmetal must be clean and straight like it is here, because we all look for the iconic full-length scalloped design.  But more than just a nice shine, this one has added attraction from the details like the correct badging, cool chrome bumpers, and the stylish wire wheel covers.

While the white vinyl top has the crisp appearance of a recent investment, we like it even better when the roof is down â€“ that's probably why this was order with a power top! The reason why this looks so good open to the world is because the red seats, red carpets, red door panels, and red dash all coordinate so nicely with the exterior.  There's even a red boot cover.  And everyone loves the look of the premium Pony package interior.  But as much as this classic can carry family and friends, it's really the driver who's the most important.  That's why you get that classic three-spoke sports steering wheel with the perfect thin grip.  And your right hand may never want to leave that Hurst shifter.

Under the hood are some nice upgrades like the Cobra valve covers and the bright air grabber, but there is nothing that gets in the way of the reliable power that comes from Ford's trusty 289 cubic-inch V8.  In fact, this is a true droptop for people who enjoy the feeling of the road.  So you're going to love the total control you get from the four-speed manual transmission, and your favorite soundtrack will be the growl of the dual exhaust as you shift through the optimal powerband.
A red '65 Mustang convertible is the kind of icon that gets all the right attention.  So when it looks great and is priced so right, we know you need to hurry to grab this deal.  Call today!!!

description: The year is 1965, Racing driver Jim Clark wins the Indianapolis 500, and later wins the Formula One world driving championship in the same year. While this gorgeous Ford Mustang rolls off the assembly line, trying to keep up with the demand of the public. Now recently rebuilt starting with the 289 V8, A/C, power steering, backed by an automatic transmission, digital dash, vinyl interior. Lee Iacocca's assistant general manager and chief engineer, Donald N. Frey was the head engineer for the T-5 projectÃ¢?"supervising the overall development of the car in a record 18 monthsÃ¢?"while Iacocca himself championed the project as Ford Division general manager. The T-5 prototype was a two-seat, mid-mounted engine roadster. This vehicle employed the German Ford Taunus V4 engine. It was claimed that the decision to abandon the two-seat design was in part due to the increase in sales the Thunderbird had seen when enlarged from a two-seater to a 2+2 in 1958. Thus, a four-seat car with full space for the front bucket seats, as originally planned, and a rear bench seat with significantly less space than was common at the time, were standard. A "Fastback 2+2", first manufactured on August 17, 1964, enclosed the trunk space under a sweeping exterior line similar to the second series Corvette Sting Ray and European sports cars such as the Jaguar E-Type coupe.Favorable publicity articles appeared in 2,600 newspapers the next morning, the day the car was "officially" revealed. description: We know you stopped to look at this 1965 Ford Mustang because it's a cool classic in a great color combo, and it's all for an affordable price.  But when you see that this coupe has also gone under a rotisserie restoration that even added A/C to the interior, well then, you know this is the perfect pony for you.

There are plenty of nice red Mustangs out there, so we tend to notice when someone takes the time to invest in a respray of original shade of Y-code Silver Blue metallic.  It has the kind of shine that can be a standout in a crowd.  But more than just paint, it's a true '65 Mustang â€“ the kind of American icon that evokes memories the moment anyone catches sight of the pony on the grille.  So it's hard to go wrong with this classic coupe.  Every piece of brightwork is complete and near pristine, from the wide front bumper, to the side scoops, to the Mustang-branded gas cap.  And everyone love the sight of Mag wheels with pony center caps.  But what really strikes you about this coupe is the straightness of the panels.  We have a large photo file that shows this coupe's journey back from the dead as it undergoes a full rotisserie restoration.

You can tell there was plenty left in the restoration budget to get the interior right. It starts with the factory-correct blue crinkle vinyl seats.  They coordinate nicely with the side panels and even the exterior paint to give this coupe the appeal of a deep blue ocean.  You get all the great iconic features like the bucket seats, dual cowl dash, and the three-spoke sports steering wheel with pony logo center cap.  But then there are also nice subtle upgrades like the retrosound radio that keeps the classic knob-style appearance while upgrading you to a digital AM/FM tuner with cassette player.  Plus, the cold air conditioning has been upgraded to R134a to keep you cool while looking cool.

Under the hood, Ford's trusty and powerful 289 cubic-inch motor is nicely presented.  The bold blue block, valve covers, and air topper all nicely radiating from within the dark engine bay.  You can tell there was a solid investment here, because it has all the right features â€“ from the factory decals to the FoMoCo coolant overflow bag.  It's the kind of total package that will make you proud to show off.  And more than just look good, this is a cool cruiser with features like   the C4 three-speed automatic transmission and modern grip of BF Goodrich T/A tires.

Not only will you love showing off this coupe, but that full restoration photo file will make for a terrific book to take everyone through this icon's rebirth.  It's amazing you can get such a cool car and a cool story for such an exceptional price.  But that's only true if you're first to grab this deal.  Don't miss out, call today!
title: 1965 Ford Mustang

description: Time to have a ton of fun for quite an affordable price.  After all, we bet you'd expect to pay much more for a 1965 Ford Mustang with a wild paint job, custom interior, four-on-the-floor, and an upgraded V8 under that cool Cobra Jet hood.

We could tell you this is a red-hot deal, but you already know that from the paint.  The custom flames make a bold first impression as they consume the front end and make their way down this first-year Mustang's iconic profile.  But don't let that be your only deciding factor on this coupe.  Take a look at the rest of the quality work.  For example, the gray paint that covers the rest of the car has a great metallic element and plenty of shine to make sure that the whole body looks great.  And you have great iconic details like the fog lights from the GT package, and GT wheels from the later pony cars.  And speaking of those muscle Mustangs, don't you just love how this one utilizes the Cobra Jet shaker hood?

Inside, the custom performance feeling continues with a leather bucket seat interior borrowed from a later-model Mustang.  That means you get upgraded comfort, while still getting the iconic pony embroidered on the seatback.  Plus, the cup holder center console is a great place to rest your elbow when your right hand is on the Hurst stick shift.  And your left hand is going to love the grippy Gant GT sports steering wheel.   While this has an upgraded AM/FM/CD stereo, all these performance pieces are a clear sign your favorite soundtrack will really be the rumble of the dual exhaust.

While the interior and exterior have a bold standout presence, the engine bay is all about getting down to business.  Within the black walls you can see the 289 cubic-inch motor's bold blue block radiating power.  Plus, with the fresh air topper feeding the Edelbrock four-barrel carburetor, you know there's extra power coming from the V8.  You have complete control over this motor thanks to the four-speed top loader stick shift.  As you look over all the photos, you're going to spot all the right supporting components, like front disc brakes and an adjustable coilover rear suspension.  There's even a Champion aluminum radiator w/electric fan to keep this whole package running cool.

So beneath the cool custom appearance lies the right pieces for a sturdy performance machine.  It's amazing all of this can be so affordable, but you're not the only one who thinks so.  That's why you need to hurry to grab this deal. Call now!
